<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94: SEMIFINALS; SPOTLIGHT; NOW ENGLISH REALLY WISH THEY WERE 
HERE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM TUOHY, Times London Bureau 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The more chauvinistic portions of the British press reacted to Germany's loss 
in the World Cup with glee. Other writers sounded the what-might-have-been 
theme if England had qualified for the Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
 In the Sun, Brian Woolnough commented: "There is romance and justice left in 
the World Cup after all. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Germans are out. Good riddance! 
</P>
<P>
 "There were no handkerchiefs needed by neutrals in New York's Giants Stadium. 
No, we were delighted to say goodby to the world champions. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have had enough of their diving, play-acting, cheating and arrogance over 
the years. Yes, of course, they can play and their record is incredible. But if 
ever a bully needed a kick in the Bulgars, it was Lothar Matthaeus and his 
men." 
</P>
<P>
 And from his colleague at the Sun, John Sadler: "These finals, dramatic and 
exciting as they have been, have not yet produced a side that would unduly 
trouble a well prepared, well managed England. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "I am not claiming England would have beaten (Brazil), but England are better 
than many of the teams that qualified for these final stages." 
</P>
<P>
 And the Independent answered its question: How might England have fared? "The 
presence of seven European nations in the quarterfinals suggests at least 
participation in the second round." 
</P>
</TEXT>
