<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: COMPANY TOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AMY HARMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 New media: Two Time Warner subsidiaries, Home Box Office and Warner Music 
Group, have invested about $5 million to form a multimedia company called 
Inscape, to be headed by developer Michael Nash and based in West Los Angeles. 
The venture reflects the growing realization among big media companies looking 
to get into the interactive business that good talent is hard to find."So much 
in this industry is not what it appears, but Michael Nash is for real," HBO 
Executive Vice President John Billock said. Nash left Voyager Co. when it moved 
from Malibu to New York last year. He was the executive producer of the 
critically acclaimed CD-ROM "Freak Show," Inscape's first title, which Nash 
describes as "a cross between 'Sim City' and 'Twin Peaks.' " AMY HARMON 
