<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Randy Lewis, HOCKLEY I; Jon Nalick 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ALL OR NOTHING: You know those Barbra Streisand tickets turned back in because 
of her four postponed concerts at The Pond of Anaheim? You'd better have deep 
pockets if you want any of them. Late Monday, the $50 tickets were sold out; so 
were the $150 tickets. . . . The $350 seats were the only ones left -- and only 
for the July 22 and July 24 concerts. The July 18 and July 20 concerts were 
sold out, according to Ticketmaster. 
</P>
<P>
 NIGHT FLIGHT: If you like going out, maybe there's no such thing as too many 
nightclubs in Orange County. Here's the latest: the Airporter Club. It's at the 
Airporter Garden Hotel in Irvine, across MacArthur Boulevard from John Wayne 
Airport. . . . Thursday's grand opening includes three live bands, free food 
and drink, Los Angeles Rams cheerleaders handing out free key chains, and 458 
square feet of dance floor. The club will play live music all nights except 
Mondays, when a deejay is in charge. 
</P>
<P>
 TOUGH TEACHER? Rudy Lozano, 55, who teaches at Lathrop Intermediate School in 
Santa Ana, recently won first place in a statewide power-lifting competition 
for his age bracket. Now he's training for the nationals. . . . Lozano weighs 
165 pounds, but was able to lift more than 350 pounds. . . . Lozano says 
there's a purpose: to show young people what they can accomplish with 
exercising and staying drug free. There's also a bonus, he quips: "I have 
little problem keeping control of my classes. It helps." 
</P>
<P>
 FIVE TO GO: Remember those 14 people who left Huntington Beach on foot June 18 
heading for Central Park in New York City? . . . . Now they are five. Desert 
temperatures reaching 117 degrees exhausted some of the runners in the 
corporate-sponsored Trans America Footrace. A few were weakened by a 
"dysentery-type illness" they picked up in Utah, a spokeswoman says. Now the 
die-hards have left the desert and are climbing the mountains of Colorado. They 
expect to reach New York Aug. 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
