329 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; LITTLE ONES GET IN THE SWIM AT CITY PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTINA LIMA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As 11-month-old Evan Mathers splashed his hands in the water at the Buena High 
School pool at the beginning of his swim class on Monday, his mother, Kym, knew 
exactly what to do. 
</P>
<P>
 She held the baby up out of the water, looked into his eyes and told him that 
he was going under, but only for a moment. "One, two, three -- and down you 
go," Mathers said as she quickly immersed the child, who came up smiling. "He 
feels much more comfortable in the water than when we had just started." 
</P>
<P>
 Teaching a child to safely go under water is one of the many techniques that 
Mathers and other parents learn at the infant and preschool aquatic summer 
program offered by the city of Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 The 10-lesson course at the Buena High pool aims to teach infants and children 
ages 6 months to 3 years how to kick, blow bubbles, float and get ready to 
learn to swim.  
</P>
<P>
 The 30-minute classes begin with signing songs and bouncing in the water 
before the day's work begins. 
</P>
<P>
 "For the youngest, the goal is to make them comfortable in the water and to 
show their parents how to teach them basic water safety techniques," said Mari 
Alsip, the pool manager. "The parents learn more than the kids." 
</P>
<P>
 Alsip said parents often do not know how to treat infants in the water. 
</P>
<P>
 "You have to speak to them as if they understand what you are saying," Alsip 
said. "And the more you repeat the same technique, the more likely they are to 
learn." 
</P>
<P>
 As the babies grow older, they can continue taking summer swimming classes 
offered by the city. Since 1974, the city has provided a variety of classes not 
only for infants but also for children ages 3 to 17, Alsip said. 
</P>
<P>
 Brazaleen Lyons, 35, has enrolled all five of her children in city swimming 
classes for the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't want them to be afraid of water," Lyons said as she taught her 
7-month-old baby how to kick in the water. "And at the same time, I don't want 
them to hop in without knowing what they are doing." CHRISTINA LIMA 
</P>
</TEXT>
