<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING & FINANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ex-Fed Governor Says Further Rate Hikes Needed: Wayne Angell, now chief 
economist at Bear, Stearns & Co., said that to avoid a recession in the next 
three years, the Federal Reserve Board needs to raise the federal funds rate -- 
the interest rate that banks charge one another for overnight loans -- by 100 
basis points, to 5.25%. The Fed has raised the rate 25 basis points four times 
this year. Many analysts expect to see rates rise again, perhaps as much as 50 
basis points, before the policy-making Federal Open Market Committee convenes 
again Aug. 16. 
</P>
