<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; REPLACEMENT NAMED FOR OUSTED DEAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The chairman of electrical and computer engineering at UC Irvine has been 
named acting dean of the university's School of Engineering, UCI officials 
announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Professor Allen Stubberud will succeed William Sirignano as dean Sept. 1, UCI 
spokesman Scott Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Chancellor Laurel L. Wilkening ousted Sirignano as dean of the School of 
Engineering in March on the recommendation of a faculty committee after a 
review. 
</P>
<P>
 Sirignano plans to return to full-time teaching in the department of 
mechanical and aerospace engineering and continue his research in 
thermodynamics and fluid mechanics, Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Stubberud, 60, has extensive experience as a dean of the UCI engineering 
school, Nelson said; he served as dean from 1978 until 1983. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a difficult job," Stubberud said. "You've got to interact with a lot of 
people, administrators, faculty members, industrial people and students. You've 
got several different constituencies you're trying to please." 
</P>
<P>
 Stubberud said he did not apply for the permanent dean's slot. He estimated 
that a search for the next dean would last until next summer. 
</P>
<P>
 Originally from Glendive, Mont., Stubberud said he started his career in the 
University of California system as an instructor at UCLA in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
 He joined UCI's faculty during its infancy, moving to the university in 1969 
-- four years after it opened. 
</P>
<P>
 He took a leave from UCI between 1983 and 1985, when he was appointed chief 
scientist of the U.S. Air Force in Washington, D.C. From 1987 to 1988, he 
served as director of the Electrical, Communications and Systems Engineering 
Division of the National Science Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
 Stubberud, of Irvine, said he received his bachelor's degree in electrical 
engineering from the University of Idaho and his master's and doctoral degrees 
in engineering from UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
 He will continue to serve as chairman of the electrical and computer 
engineering department at UCI during his stint as dean.ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</TEXT>
