<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: PARIS; GERMANS BACK IN PARIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It's been 49 years and 11 months since the goose-stepping German army was 
driven from the streets of Paris by the Allies in World War II. Now, on 
Thursday, German soldiers will be back for the first time, marching down the 
Champs-Elysees as invited guests of the French government in the annual 
Bastille Day parade. 
</P>
<P>
 The participation of the German army in France's Republic Day festivities, 
barely a month after German leaders were shut out of D-Day commemorations, is 
viewed by many in France as a chance to bury the past. An opinion poll 
conducted by Le Figaro newspaper last week found 58% of the French believe it 
is a good idea to let the Germans join the parade, as against 34% who are 
opposed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071294-0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 059994 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 12, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
World Report; Page 1; Column 2; World Report 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
